The fall of the former Soviet Union and the transformation of China from a centralized communist dictatorship into the world’s second largest economic power are indicative of the monumental changes that have been taking place since the end of the Cold War and the collapse of the 20th century’s arrangements with their high tension and great undermining of international stability.

During this period, less than 50 years after the massive evacuation from Europe of millions of Jews, Armenians, Poles and others, a flip in the 21st century has begun with another massive wave of Palestinian refugees fleeing the armed conflict.

The Palestinian expatriation stems from the mid-1900’s, but has now reached unprecedented proportions: the trauma that interprets the majority of Arab public had become ingrained in collective consciousness, and after several changes in the Palestinian national leadership, a myth has been formed that won the hearts and minds of Arabs about the centrality of the “Palestinian question”. How the Palestinian leadership link its own political interests with the foreign affairs of Arab governments, which it constantly manipulates on the sidelines.

In contrast to the Palestinians, the Jewish people did not want much of anything from Arab governments and remain politically independent. The partition plan that was rejected by the United Nations in 1947 led to the establishment of the State of Israel, which was immediately attacked by the neighboring governments and therefore established a strong defense system that protected the country. Cooperation with the United States began early and became deeply rooted
